\subsubsection{{Research}} Research  is the systematic inquiry into the study of situations to establish facts and reach new conclusion.

\subsubsection{{Data science}}  Data science is the systemic study of structure and behavior of collecting, organizing, evaluating, and interpreting data.  The interpretation phase refers population characteristics from sampling.

\subsubsection{{Data}} Data are information collected from the population for further analysis.

\subsubsection{Theory}  Theory is a statement used to explain a situation, eg., 
is there a difference about alcohol awareness  between health and safety class and a statistics class among college stadents.

\subsubsection{Hypothesis}  Hypothesis is an explanation about an association between events, eg.,  
alcohol awareness among college students is the same between  students enrolled in a health and safety class and for those enrolled in a statistics class.

\subsubsection{Observations}  Observations are collected data to test hypothesis, eg., a random sample of students enrolled in a health and safety class and those enrolled in a statistics class which surveys alcohol awareness.



\subsubsection{Empirical Generalizations}  Empirical generalizations are made to assess the theory after analyzing the data, eg., 
A study of alcohol awareness among college students reported a higher awareness for students enrolled in a health and safety class than for those enrolled in a statistics class.

\subsubsection{Variables and Cases}

\subsubsection{Variables}

\begin{itemize}
\item Variables are attributes of a person (case).
  \begin{itemize}
  \item Examples: socio-economic stats such as age, gender, race, and social class.
  \end{itemize}

\item Theories and hypotheses are asserting the association between variables.
  \begin{itemize}
  \item A theory may identify some variables as causes (independent variables) and others as effects or results (dependent variable).
  \end{itemize}

\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Case}

\begin{itemize}
\item Case is a collection of variables from a person (entity).
  \begin{itemize}
  \item Cases are from groups; for example, members from churches or unions or cities or states.
  \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Example}

Describe  the color of eyes of students in this class.

\begin{itemize}
\item Variable is color of eyes of students
\item Data is color such as black, blue, brown, green, hazel.
\item Cases are students from this class.
\item Appropriate analysis include:
	\begin{itemize}
	\item frequency (number) of students who have brown eyes.
	\item percent of students who have blue eyes.
	\item bar chart showing the percentage of each color of eyes.
	\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}	
     
\section{Types of Statistics}


\subsection{Descriptive Statistics}

Descriptive statistics are used to explain the basic features of the data in a study.

There are three methods of describing data.

\begin{enumerate}
\item {\bf{Univariate}} descriptive statistics -- summarizes {\bf{one variable at a time}}, such as 
numerical, graphical,  % averages, percentages, charts and graphs:
	\begin{itemize}
	\item The average IQ of the class is 120,  also range, variance, etc. 
	\item The percent of females taking Stat 2830 this semester is 55 percent.
	\end{itemize}

\item {\bf{Bivariate}} descriptive statistics -- summarizes {\bf{two variables at a time}}, such as 
looking for relationships between two variables that describe strength and direction.
	\begin{itemize}
	\item The relationship between college juniors and seniors credit card debt is  positive and strong.
	
	\end{itemize}	

\item {\bf{Multivariate}} descriptive statistics -- summarizes {\bf{three or more variables at a time}}, such as 
looking for relationships between three or more variables that describe strength and direction.
	\begin{itemize}
	\item It has been alleged that obvious consumption is a way for men to show their status to other males.  
	A recent study looked at the changes in testosterone level in response to changes in his status created by 
	using a product such as an old car versus a new sports car.  The subjects of the study were told to drive 
	on a busy urban avenue or on a less traveled rural highway.

	\end{itemize}	
\end{enumerate}


\subsection{Inferential Statistics}

Inferential statistics makes a general statement about a population based on a sample se;ected from that population.

